 "id": "yam-window-is-a-qualification-corridor",
 "title": "Year 1 is a certification-and-qualification corridor, not a selling year — the 3% obtainable factor silently borrows years 2–3",
 "narrative": "The obtainableFactor of 0.03 sits mid-band of generic SOM benchmarks, and it was already revised down from 6%, so it reads as conservative. But the benchmark sources themselves define SOM over a 1–3 or 3–5 year capture window, not a single year — while the entry sequence for a pre-launch CE hardware entrant is cert (6–9 months: CE/TÜV, ecodesign conformity, WEEE/EORI) followed by a 12–18 month DC hardware sales cycle. Months 1–9 of the YAM window produce zero bookable revenue by construction. Reference-class realized first-period shares (TryBuildCo's worked example ~0.1% of SAM; Tractian's ~0.001% of its market) sit one to two orders of magnitude below the 1% 'floor'. The honest Year-1 number is pilots, ≈0.5–1% of SAM, not 3%.",
 "category": "execution",
