   "text": "The remaining 3–6 months cannot contain a 12–18 month enterprise/DC hardware sales cycle; the benchmark sources behind the 1–5% band explicitly define SOM as a 1–3 or 3–5 year window, so applying the mid-band to Year 1 double-counts calendar time",
   "refs": [
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c4",
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c1",
    "ledger:obtainableFactor"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "Realized Year-1 capture is pilot revenue only; reference-class observations (worked example ~0.1% of SAM, real hardware entrant ~0.001% of market, 30% of deployed POC systems never accepted) put the honest factor at ~0.005–0.01, roughly 5x below the curated 0.03",
   "refs": [
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c5",
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c6",
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c8"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "0.03 was already revised DOWN from 0.06 and sits mid-band of two independent benchmark sources — it looks like the conservative choice the profile asked for. What the surface hides is that the benchmark's denominator is a multi-year capture window: the 'conservative' Year-1 number silently imports years 2 and 3.",
 "expectedObviousness": "medium",
 "falsifier": "A signed volume purchase order (not a pilot or POC) from a CE operator closed within 9 months of launch, at a run-rate consistent with ≥1% of SAM.",
